  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Memorial of Congratulation on the Feast of Hamseong
  author: Kim Geuk-gi
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Your subject humbly submits this memorial.

    I have learned that Your Majesty received the felicitations of all courts and peoples on the eleventh day of this month, the Feast of Hamseong. A thousand years of sacred longevity thus commence—behold how the stars bloom like rainbows over the luminous waters, and the tribute of ten thousand nations surpasses even the ceremonial silks and jade of ancient Tushan. Heaven and earth respond in turn, and all creatures near and far rejoice. Your subject dances with sincere joy and bows in deepest reverence.

    Reverently I reflect: Your Majesty possesses the benevolence of the sage-king Tang and embodies the celestial mandate of the great Shun. Such supreme virtue and mighty works pierce through the three luminaries above and reach to the nine depths below. Your vast dominion and countless peoples encompass all within heaven and earth, making the four seas your home. The myriad nations flourish in peace, and abundant blessings flow forth of their own accord. How much more fitting, then, that in this auspicious age, we gather to celebrate the boundless felicities bestowed upon you.

    Though your subject holds the tiger seal and dutifully guards the fish tally, having been absent from the imperial presence for many months, I am now granted this fortunate day. I dare not hope for Your Majesty's years to rival the heavens themselves in their endless duration, yet I earnestly pray that your sacred longevity shall never fade. Unable to contain the reverence and awe that fills my heart as I gaze upon this moment of imperial glory, I humbly send my envoy to present this memorial of felicitation.
  footnotes:
    - The Feast of Hamseong (함성절) was a significant court celebration, likely commemorating a royal occasion or auspicious date.
    - Tushan (塗山) refers to an ancient place associated with the sage-king Yu and ceremonial tribute exchanges.
    - The 'tiger seal' and 'fish tally' (虎節, 魚領) are symbols of official authority and responsibility in the imperial bureaucracy.
    - The 'three luminaries' (三光) traditionally refer to the sun, moon, and stars; the 'nine depths' (九泉) represent the underworld in classical cosmology.
